@U A It's cool, realised I'd been surrounded by narcissistic people my whole life too. Anyway understanding the manipulations is vital, because then you start to label it...like say to yourself oooh there's a bit of shaming with a good dose of guilt tripping, oh another character assination, look at that they're triangulating me again, I see, here comes the love-bombing again, trying to buy me now with their offer of money, look there goes the future faking with the promise of a trip or whatever. I see they're complimenting me now ( it's not genuine) so I know they're about to ask for something from me now. Oh they're now mirroring me to persuade me to do something. Notice the triangulation, it's a favourite of the narcissist, oh I see they're projecting onto me ( they can't look inside themselves ) here comes the blameshifting, a bit of contrition, mmm using intimidation now to keep me in line etc...Once you label and recognise the way that person makes you feel and label the behaviour then you start to realise the game they're playing and that you can better deal with it because you can see things clearly. Eventually whether family or not you'll come to the conclusion that you're better off keeping a distance between yourself and the manipulator regardless of the loyalty to the parental or intimate relationship. I think the gas lighting is the worse! However with that said, nearly everyone manipulates for good or bad, so it's important to recognise our own manipulative behaviours too, especially when it's been modelled to us from childhood. It's not about demonising a person but more about our own self-protection and emotional growth and maturity.
A good book to read is 'Manipulation'  by H.G Tudor, there's plenty more but that combined with 'Escape' are really insightful books.
Sorry about the length of the message but really hope it helps. Good luck with your future xxxxx

